📖 What IAM Is
Core security service in AWS.

Manages users, groups, roles, and policies.

## Ensures the right people and applications have the right level of access.

🎯 Why IAM Is Used
Authentication → Verify who is trying to access AWS (user, app, service).

Authorization → Decide what they can do (read, write, delete, etc.).

Granular control → Apply least privilege (give only the permissions needed).

Security compliance → Enforce MFA, password policies, and access boundaries.

## Scalability → Manage permissions across large teams and multiple accounts.

🌍 Where IAM Is Used
Users & Groups → Human accounts (developers, admins).

Roles → Temporary access for applications, services, or cross-account access.

Policies → JSON documents that define permissions (Allow/Deny).

## Federation → Integrate with external identity providers (Google, Microsoft AD, etc.).

⚡ Example Scenario
You’re hosting a static website on S3 + CloudFront:

IAM ensures only you (admin) can upload files to the S3 bucket.

A bucket policy allows the public to read files (view the website).

